Jazz. I told you to go home.

254
00:12:48.190 --> 00:12:51.049
How fast were you going
when you hit this?

255
00:12:52.100 --> 00:12:55.279
Now see here...homey.

256
00:12:58.039 --> 00:12:59.120
My lady and I

257
00:12:59.139 --> 00:13:02.269
are trying to have
an intimate moment.

258
00:13:02.289 --> 00:13:04.269
Oh. I get it.

259
00:13:04.289 --> 00:13:07.059
You're trying
to make me jealous.

260
00:13:07.080 --> 00:13:10.009
Well. it worked like a charm.

261
00:13:10.029 --> 00:13:12.039
Beat it. buddy.

262
00:13:12.059 --> 00:13:14.059
How dare you talk
to me like that?

263
00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:17.230
Do you have any idea who I am?

264
00:13:17.250 --> 00:13:20.070
A really bad cook?

265
00:13:20.090 --> 00:13:24.230
Trevor. could you excuse us
for a moment. please?

266
00:13:24.250 --> 00:13:27.279
I have never been so
insulted in my life.

267
00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.059
Blind people recognize me.

268
00:13:32.039 --> 00:13:33.240
I could kill you.

269
00:13:33.259 --> 00:13:36.179
Okay. baby. Hurt me.

270
00:13:38.090 --> 00:13:41.169
Look. I am not gonna
let you screw this up for me.

271
00:13:41.190 --> 00:13:44.230
Trevor is
a wonderful man.

272
00:13:44.250 --> 00:13:47.080
But I'm Jazz..

273
00:13:47.100 --> 00:13:49.149
...the lover of all lovers.

274
00:13:51.110 --> 00:13:54.009
I put the "afro"
in aphrodisiac.

275
00:13:55.059 --> 00:13:57.019
So lose the stiff

276
00:13:57.039 --> 00:13:59.049
and I'll be waiting
in the pool house.

277
00:14:00.149 --> 00:14:03.149
Oh. and fix yourself up
a little.

278
00:14:05.250 --> 00:14:07.019
[sighs]

279
00:14:10.019 --> 00:14:11.179
[music on television]

280
00:14:11.200 --> 00:14:14.179
What happened
to your friend?

281
00:14:14.200 --> 00:14:17.169
[sighs]
We.. Don't worry about him.

282
00:14:17.190 --> 00:14:18.200
What are you watching?

283
00:14:18.220 --> 00:14:21.190
Oh. one of those
silly sentimental films.

284
00:14:21.210 --> 00:14:23.129
Formula stuff.

285
00:14:23.149 --> 00:14:25.129
Can I watch with you?

286
00:14:26.110 --> 00:14:28.090
Sure.

287
00:14:28.110 --> 00:14:30.210
But I have to go home
in a few minutes.

288
00:14:35.120 --> 00:14:38.149
♪ Memories ♪

289
00:14:38.169 --> 00:14:42.059
♪ Like the corners of my mind ♪

290
00:14:45.129 --> 00:14:50.100
♪ Misty water-colored memories ♪

291
00:14:50.120 --> 00:14:54.019
♪ Of the way we were ♪

292
00:14:55.120 --> 00:14:58.019
♪ Scattered pictures ♪

293
00:14:59.110 --> 00:15:03.169
♪ Of the smiles
we left behind.. ♪♪

294
00:15:10.080 --> 00:15:11.169
I don't wanna alarm
either one of you

295
00:15:11.190 --> 00:15:13.039
but it's about 20 degrees
in here

296
00:15:13.059 --> 00:15:15.059
and it's only gonna get worse.

297
00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:20.240
Carlton's log.

298
00:15:20.259 --> 00:15:22.230
I hate dad!

299
00:15:27.019 --> 00:15:29.200
You know. this wood
is just too wet to ignite.

300
00:15:29.220 --> 00:15:31.200
We need something dry.

301
00:15:31.220 --> 00:15:34.120
I'm afraid it's gonna
have to be something that's

302
00:15:34.139 --> 00:15:36.269
near and dear to all of us.

303
00:15:36.289 --> 00:15:40.019
Oh. come on. Uncle Phil.
at least knock him out first.

304
00:15:41.070 --> 00:15:42.220
I'm talking about
the money. Will.

305
00:15:42.240 --> 00:15:45.120
Uh-uh!

306
00:15:45.139 --> 00:15:49.220
Will. do you wanna die
with $25.000 by your side

307
00:15:49.240 --> 00:15:51.279
or do you want to live
to see tomorrow?

308
00:15:56.129 --> 00:15:58.159
I'm thinking.
I'm thinking. alright?

309
00:15:58.179 --> 00:15:59.279
I'm afraid
there's no other choice.

310
00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.220
Alright. Alright.
Alright.

311
00:16:02.240 --> 00:16:07.059
Look. can I just have a few
minutes alone with the guys?

312
00:16:07.080 --> 00:16:08.240
Okay. Okay.

313
00:16:17.100 --> 00:16:21.080
Dad. when you throw
that money into the fire

314
00:16:21.100 --> 00:16:23.279
if I lose my head
and leap in after it

315
00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.049
you'll pull me out. right?

316
00:16:28.200 --> 00:16:33.080
Son. there are more important
things in life than money.

317
00:16:33.100 --> 00:16:37.090
Yeah. but I can't
get a date. either.

318
00:16:47.100 --> 00:16:49.059
[sighs]

319
00:16:49.080 --> 00:16:51.200
Alright. here's the money.

320
00:17:05.099 --> 00:17:06.200
What?

321
00:17:11.259 --> 00:17:13.269
[Will moaning]

322
00:17:18.220 --> 00:17:21.079
[moaning louder]

323
00:17:21.099 --> 00:17:24.109
Whoa-whoa! Whoa!
Was that Andrew or Ben?

324
00:17:24.130 --> 00:17:27.140
- It was Ben.
- Ohh..

325
00:17:27.160 --> 00:17:28.279
Oh. I'm sorry. Ben.

326
00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:30.059
You was one
of the few white people

327
00:17:30.079 --> 00:17:33.029
I could really count on.

328
00:17:33.049 --> 00:17:35.049
Carlton's log.

329
00:17:35.069 --> 00:17:37.059
Will has been reduced
to a pathetic shell

330
00:17:37.079 --> 00:17:39.259
of his former self.

331
00:17:39.279 --> 00:17:42.220
I. on the other hand.
have the strength of ten men.

332
00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:46.210
Will's log..

333
00:17:46.230 --> 00:17:49.000
...is about to connect
with Carlton's head!

334
00:17:49.019 --> 00:17:52.130
Hey! Hey! Hey! Hey!
Hey! Hey. Hey. Will.

335
00:17:52.150 --> 00:17:55.039
Give me the log.

336
00:17:55.059 --> 00:17:57.180
That's not why I brought
you two up here.

337
00:18:02.069 --> 00:18:04.190
Oh. I really blew it.

338
00:18:04.210 --> 00:18:06.099
All I wanted to do
was spend time with you

339
00:18:06.119 --> 00:18:08.210
before you went off to college.

340
00:18:10.099 --> 00:18:14.019
You know. there's a better
way
of doing it. Uncle Phil.

341
00:18:14.039 --> 00:18:17.130
Perhaps a matinee
and a box of Raisinets.

342
00:18:19.059 --> 00:18:22.180
Raisinets? I hate Raisinets.

343
00:18:22.200 --> 00:18:24.119
Could we get some Goobers?

344
00:18:26.250 --> 00:18:29.269
It's not the same.

345
00:18:29.289 --> 00:18:34.190
Some of the best memories of my
life are camping with my father.

346
00:18:35.269 --> 00:18:38.019
He taught me how
to hunt and fish

347
00:18:38.039 --> 00:18:41.000
how to pitch a tent.

348
00:18:41.019 --> 00:18:43.289
I'm guessing he didn't teach
you how to use a compass.

349
00:18:52.289 --> 00:18:55.210
[sighs]
Now that he's gone..

350
00:18:56.279 --> 00:18:58.130
...I really miss him.

351
00:19:00.279 --> 00:19:03.130
I really appreciate
what we had together.

352
00:19:05.250 --> 00:19:07.109
He was quite a man.

353
00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.259
I learned so much from him.

354
00:19:11.279 --> 00:19:14.079
[wind whistling]

355
00:19:14.099 --> 00:19:16.089
Yeah. that's decent.
Uncle Phil.

356
00:19:16.109 --> 00:19:19.019
At least you had somebody
to teach you stuff. you
know?

357
00:19:19.039 --> 00:19:21.059
I had to learn
everything on my own.

358
00:19:21.079 --> 00:19:25.029
I mean. my mom was working
all the time and everything.

359
00:19:25.049 --> 00:19:27.160
Like. I-I always wanted
to roller skate

360
00:19:27.180 --> 00:19:29.140
but. you know. I didn't
even really know how to do
it.

361
00:19:29.160 --> 00:19:33.150
So. I used to put on one
skate
and push with the other foot.

362
00:19:35.059 --> 00:19:37.039
It never seemed like
I could be fast enough

363
00:19:37.059 --> 00:19:40.140
to keep up with
the other kids. though.

364
00:19:40.160 --> 00:19:42.240
You know. actually that's how I
felt when I came to Bel-Air

365
00:19:42.259 --> 00:19:46.130
you know. like everybody
had two skates

366
00:19:46.150 --> 00:19:48.269
and I was trying
to keep up with one.

367
00:19:51.160 --> 00:19:53.160
Um..

368
00:19:53.180 --> 00:19:55.210
Thanks for my other skate.
Uncle Phil.

369
00:19:58.089 --> 00:19:59.240
[dramatic music]

370
00:20:01.210 --> 00:20:04.049
For a long time.
it gave me nightmares.

371
00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:09.019
Having to witness
an injustice like that..

372
00:20:11.029 --> 00:20:12.200
...it was a constant reminder

373
00:20:12.220 --> 00:20:15.000
of how unfair
this world can be.

374
00:20:17.150 --> 00:20:20.140
I can still hear them
taunting him.

375
00:20:22.029 --> 00:20:25.009
"Silly rabbit.
Trix are for kids."

376
00:20:35.230 --> 00:20:39.039
How come they just couldn't
give him some cereal?

377
00:20:46.269 --> 00:20:49.200
Oh. you guys.
wake up. wake up!

378
00:20:49.220 --> 00:20:51.059
Oh. man.

379
00:20:54.009 --> 00:20:57.210
Oh. We made it. We made it.
Uncle Phil. wake up!

380
00:20:57.230 --> 00:21:00.190
Vivian. Vivian.
I'm not a machine!

381
00:21:07.269 --> 00:21:10.119
- Come on. dad. it's morning.
- Oh..

382
00:21:10.140 --> 00:21:12.170
You know. it stopped snowing.
Come on.

383
00:21:12.190 --> 00:21:15.089
Let's get the hell out of here
and find a Denny's.

384
00:21:16.240 --> 00:21:19.140
Uncle Phil. if I ever agree
to go camping with you all

385
00:21:19.160 --> 00:21:22.279
just hold my head underwater
till I stop struggling.

386
00:21:29.200 --> 00:21:31.019
[indistinct chatter]

387
00:21:31.039 --> 00:21:32.190
Whoa. Whoa.
What's happening?

388
00:21:32.210 --> 00:21:34.119
Right this way. guys.
Right this way.

389
00:21:34.140 --> 00:21:37.059
Come right over here.
Right over here.

390
00:21:37.079 --> 00:21:40.140
Hey. guys. listen. I'm Ed Barker
from station KCBE.

391
00:21:40.160 --> 00:21:43.079
Congratulations. guys.
You did it.

392
00:21:43.099 --> 00:21:44.180
- W-we did?
- That's right.

393
00:21:44.200 --> 00:21:45.190
Now what are your names?

394
00:21:45.210 --> 00:21:47.240
W-well. I'm innocent Will

395
00:21:47.259 --> 00:21:50.150
a-and this is Uncle Phil.
attorney-at-law

396
00:21:50.170 --> 00:21:52.029
and this is little Carlton.

397
00:21:52.049 --> 00:21:55.130
H-he's trying to find his way
back to the circus.

398
00:21:55.150 --> 00:21:57.259
- What did we do?
- A-and was it legal?

399
00:21:57.279 --> 00:21:59.180
Hey. yo. homie. we was gonna
give the money back. man.

400
00:21:59.200 --> 00:22:02.009
- But my uncle--
- Give it back?

401
00:22:02.029 --> 00:22:04.140
It's yours to keep.

402
00:22:04.160 --> 00:22:08.029
See. you just found the last
clue in the KCBE scavenger hunt.

403
00:22:08.049 --> 00:22:09.269
You found the prize money!

404
00:22:09.289 --> 00:22:12.000
[cheering]

405
00:22:13.069 --> 00:22:14.279
Well. now. tell me
something. guys.

406
00:22:15.009 --> 00:22:18.269
How does it feel to be rich?

407
00:22:18.289 --> 00:22:23.140
It's terrible. Uncle Backdraft
made us burn it.

408
00:22:23.160 --> 00:22:26.089
You burned $50.000?

409
00:22:26.109 --> 00:22:28.269
50.000?

410
00:22:28.289 --> 00:22:31.059
You said it was 25.

411
00:22:32.109 --> 00:22:35.259
Oh. I must have miscounted.

412
00:22:35.279 --> 00:22:37.059
Ah. well.

413
00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:44.109
[instrumental music]

414
00:22:47.259 --> 00:22:49.230
He taught me how to hunt.
how to fish

415
00:22:49.250 --> 00:22:51.140
how to pinch a tent.

416
00:22:51.160 --> 00:22:53.069
[snickering]

417
00:22:53.089 --> 00:22:54.230
You know. you pinch. you got to
pinch it right down there.

418
00:22:54.250 --> 00:22:58.140
Ooh! Ooh! Ooh!

419
00:22:58.160 --> 00:23:01.259
You know. right by the pole
where they put it up.

420
00:23:01.279 --> 00:23:04.130
[indistinct chatter]

421
00:23:04.150 --> 00:23:06.099
How to pinch a tent?

422
00:23:06.119 --> 00:23:07.279
Come here.
you cute little tent.

423
00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:10.119
I'm gonna pinch you.
You's a cute little tent.

423
